WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.000
We're running.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Good afternoon.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Today is April 16, 2013.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:19.000
April 15.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.000
April 50, 2013.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Thank you.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:31.000
And today we are in Palo Alto, California on behalf of the Civil Rights History Project.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:42.000
Supported by the Congress, the Library of Congress, the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:48.000
And this project is also supported by the Southern Oral History Program at UNC Chapel Hill.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
My name is David Kline over the interviewer today.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:56.000
With me is videographer John Bishop of Media Generation and UCLA.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:02.000
And we have with us today Dr. Clarence Jones and I just want to say thank you so much for spending time with us today.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:04.000
My pleasure.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Thank you.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:06.000
I'm glad to be here.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.000
I just out of deference to my mother.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.000
I'd like for you to use my middle initial when you were putting it in the archives.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Clarence B. Jones.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.000
My mother's name is Benjamin.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.000
And so that she seemed to be very much indeed to that name.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
So as an adult I've carried it forward.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Wonderful.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Okay.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:29.000
Let me understand that.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
And so let's start there.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Okay.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:39.000
With your birth parents and a little bit about your childhood.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Okay.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Where that brought you?

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:49.000
My parents were domestic servants when I was born.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:02:03.000
I was born over 82 years ago, 82 years ago this January, this past January, 1931 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:08.000
When I said my parents were domestic workers, specifically my mother was a maiden of cook.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:11.000
My father was a chauffeur and a gardener.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:21.000
And they worked as a domestic servant couple for J.B. Lippincott family of the J.B. Lippincott family.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:30.000
J.B. Lippincott family out of Philadelphia and into publishing into a grain.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
But a very established wealthy family.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:41.000
And J.B. Lippincott family was one of the grandums of the family, who employed my parents.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:48.000
When I was born, apparently they did not have a home of their own.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:59.000
So the home in which I came into was the home of the place where they worked.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:15.000
And I can remember before the age of about six years of age, being placed at least with three different foster families.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:28.000
And by that I mean these were adult friends of my parents, who my parents had made some arrangements.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.000
I guess you will keep young clearance, let them stay as part of the family.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:42.000
And so that's I was I was I was place with them, different families.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
This happened at least on three occasions before about the age of six years of age.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Again I don't know what prompted my mother and father to do it principally my mother.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Decided that they would place me in a boarding school, a boarding school for foster children and orphans.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Or specifically for indigent foster and orphan colored boys and Indians run by the Sisters of the Blessed Sacrament.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:41.000
And I think also by the order of the sacred heart, the nuns who ran the religious order that ran the Catholic boarding school for colored boys.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Orphans and foster children also maintain mission schools in New Mexico on the Navajo reservations.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And as a consequence, as a young boy in this boarding school for colored and indigent children.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Several of the boys there were Indians.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:28.000
And very early on I would I got accustomed to seeing a boy with long, long, big tail.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:33.000
You know, long ponytail or something. This hair would be knotted or braided.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:51.000
And the feather of band. And I remember classmates of mine, people in the school having names like Little Bear and Running Bear.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:06:09.000
And something dear. Those are their names. That's where I stayed from about the age of six years away.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:27.000
This was a Catholic private boarding school. The interesting thing about this, you notice I said there were foster children and orphans. I was neither. I had parents.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:40.000
It became clear to me that there was something wasn't right here, little contradiction because what would happen. I was there from about the age of six until 13, almost 14.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:57.000
My parents would come to visit me and they would leave. And some of the other boys would say to me, well, why are you here? Why don't they take you with them?

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:03.000
And very hard for a young person to understand it.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:23.000
During the summers, I spent three or four weeks in the summer with my parents wherever they, in the summer they usually, the woman they worked for, took a house as a summer house in Jersey Shore.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And a place called Longport, your Margate and Atlantic City. So they would be there all summer and I would go down and visit them during the summer. So I had that break.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.000
That's the only time you would actually stay with them.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:59.000
Yes, that's the only time. I didn't have Christmas with them. Didn't have Easter, didn't have holidays with them. But during this holidays I had with them. I mean, I took the summer.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:14.000
And you know, when I was in about the sixth, when I was in about the seventh grade, six of the seventh grade I developed a serious stuttering problem.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:25.000
And it was a surprise. I couldn't understand why I had begun to stammer.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:39.000
And I think as I look back on it, and as I moved on to public high school with the help of a speech teacher and just different kind of pressures operating on me, I guess.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:52.000
I was able to overcome the stammering. You wouldn't know that I studied the stammering way I speak now, the way I have spoken. So my, but the fact is, and I look back on it, I think it was that not understanding.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:09:02.000
Now, someone might listen to this story and have a certain degree of a,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:18.000
a degree of a, pathos and say, you know, I must, it's a sad thing that Master Jones, a little boy went through before. Yes and no.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:32.000
As I've gotten older, I am without question, I knew I was cared for and loved.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:56.000
Those Irish nuns loved me. They were my surrogate mothers. They loved me and had a, with a sense of discipline, you know, that stayed with me during my formative years.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:15.000
I put it this way. Had I not gone to that Catholic boarding school, I probably would have been placed in a, a, a, a de jury or meaning by law or de facto segregated school.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:33.000
And I probably would have gotten an inferior education compared to the education I actually received because as a result of going to this Catholic boarding school, there are classes of maybe about 25 boys, but there were two nuns.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:48.000
Okay. I got exempted from taking Latin in high school because I had had so much Latin in the private school, albeit religious Latin, but a lot of Latin.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:11:17.000
My publisher of the first book, what Martin say, Harper Collins. One of the editors said to me, and aside from the organization of the story in which we're going to say, Mr. Jones, we noticed that, you know, the hardly any eras, any, any grammatical eras, you know, I mean, I mean, there's some writers, you know,

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:31.000
writers of big names and so forth. And so we were amazed. And so I said to them, I said, well, let me, let me tell you, you should not be surprised because I think that it is still today.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:52.000
It is congenital, impossible for me to write a grammatically incorrect sentence in the English language. And the reason that is so is because I learned grammar by diagram sentences, which in and of itself was not so special.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:12:05.000
But I learned to do it correctly because when I did it incorrectly, there would be a pointer that would hit my knuckles. And I would say, you know better than that, Mr. Jones.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:14.000
So I made it two years old. And I can still, I can still over all those years feel that sense of correction. But, but...

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:26.000
There's always a none right over it. Always a number gave me a sense of writing correctly. And then I had a great sense for the words.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:27.000
So...

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:38.000
We're back. Great. And I will say, because this is digital recording that we're doing, we'll pause every once in a while just to save the files.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:43.000
Okay, fine. Okay, very good. I'll do that.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:13:01.000
So, you have some back to talking about this upbringing. And I wanted to ask you that, you know, this was a school for colored boys, right? But it was, I mean, you had the nuns there. It was sort of a multiracial world that you were expecting.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:16.000
Well, not so much... Well, not only... Not... Well, multiracial to the extent that the nuns were white, not... But the other students, they're all colored boys and Native Americans.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:30.000
I... Later on, we'll get a chance to talk about my later life with Martin Luther King, Jr.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:45.000
And I don't want to go there now, but I do want to use this as an example. One day, Dr. King made a comment to me, something like, you know, Clarence, you really can get very angry.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:14:14.000
At racism or racial injustice. And you really are angry, but you know, you're not anti-white today. And what do you... What do you count? Have you been that angry? How do you account for that? And I said, well, I think it's because as a young Negro boy growing up,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:28.000
spending more time quantitatively with Irish nuns than I spent quantitatively with my parents at a critical point in my life.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:43.000
Let's just break that down. The dumb and interaction of love and affection and discipline I had was from white, older women.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:58.000
And they made it very clear to me and to others when they were disciplining us, or whether I had hurt myself when I was crying,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:12.000
and they would hold me, they would comfort me, they would discipline me, but they did it with unconditional love.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:27.000
So, you know, I'm not qualified to be a psychiatrist or I'm just looking at this young boy, that that's got to have had some impact.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:42.000
If doing those formative years, you, my result is a positive, my result is a good, nothing but love and affection from these white adult women. That's what I got.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:53.000
I didn't get hate, I got love and affection. I got love and affection from my parents when I saw them. But they were my serringant parents for a period of time.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:16:06.000
So, that's a long way of saying, I said, Martin, Dr. King, I think that's the reason. I can clinically intellectually see racism for what it is.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:17.000
But it's the ideology of white supremacy. It's not the white person I hate, but I dislike. So, I just a little bit of digression.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:24.000
So, you know, so then I went, but had I not gone there. So, the consequence of going there was I got a better education, right?

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:34.000
So, when I went to public high school, as I said, I was exempted from having taken any Latin, but went to public high school. I did very well.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:41.000
I was a president, I began the President of the Honest Society, at virtually all A's.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:17:08.000
The school was Palmyra High School, Palmyra, New Jersey, Palmyra High School, Palmyra, New Jersey in Burlington County. I think my class maybe of a class of about 100, 200, maybe a class of 150, 60.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:28.000
Maybe I would say 40% of the class were colored boys and girls. This is now, this is now 1945, the 1949.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:45.000
Okay, high school, 1945, 1949. My classmates, 60% of more of whom were white, voted me as the most likely to succeed.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:18:00.000
Okay? The boy in the class was likely to succeed, and they voted some young white girl classmate of mine, whose name I can't remember now, but I was voted most likely to succeed.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:07.000
And was asked to be the class speaker on behalf of the Honest Society, speaking for my class.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:21.000
I am in my junior year in high school, near the end of my junior year, beginning my senior year.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:32.000
I went down to the Navy, and I tried to enlist. The Navy had something called a V12 program at that time.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:42.000
If you enlisted in the V-12 program, you enlisted, you went into the Navy for four or six years, but the thing is they sent you to college for four years.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:56.000
I think it was six years. And so I did that. Problem is you had to be 18. So I went down and, quote, enlisted in sign before I was 18.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:05.000
And so I get called into the principal's office one day, and so we just got a call from a Naval Recruiting Station that said, you went down and enlisted.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:16.000
Why did you lie about your age? Well, this song, so I said, I did it because I want to be able to go to college. And they said, who says you're not going to go to college?

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:25.000
I said, well, there's no way I can go to college. They said, we're going to go to college, we're very proud of you.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:41.000
The bottom line is the principal, my speech teacher, and my science teacher. They all took money out of their own pockets in order to pay for the application fees for me to apply to college.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:55.000
And so I applied to Syracuse University of Pennsylvania.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:06.000
Yale and Columbia College, Columbia University. I got into all of them.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:16.000
Syracuse because I had been a musician, often, me a four-year music, band scholarship, music scholarship.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:25.000
What did you play? Clarenette. Clarenette. I was a professional musician when I was 16, half 17 years old.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:35.000
While I was in school during the summers, I came to New York during the summers and I went to the jewelry art school in music.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:50.000
I had become a fairly good instrumentalist in any event. So I lost my train of thought.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:56.000
Oh, yeah, you got guns. Sit Syracuse over me, right? Sorry. Syracuse over me.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:07.000
And I didn't know anything about Syracuse. Somebody said, well, you know, sorry, I called. We called up there. Plus my mother's brother.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:23.000
She had a brother, my uncle, who whom I am named, Clarence. He lived in New York. And so he was an influence in my getting into Columbia College, Columbia University.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:41.000
In order for me to go, I had to get a financial aid package of scholarship. In order to get a financial aid package of scholarship, I had to maintain a B-mine of Savage, which was not easy to do.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:22:03.000
And in fact, I say to my friends out here in Silicon Valley who were interested in computer science and physics. And I said, I thought I was going to meet my academic wardeloo because I had two Nobel scientists for teachers.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:15.000
One was Linus Pauling for chemistry. I did reasonably well in chemistry. But the other person was a man by the name of Polykarp Kusch. Polykarp Kusch got the Nobel Prize for physics.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:31.000
And I've never knew up until that time what it was to go to class every day in sheer fear. I never was afraid. I was afraid of one of his fears. I'd be called on and I didn't understand what it was very difficult.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:50.000
And I never got a course of it. And two, I think that I couldn't, I had to get a C-plus. I couldn't, I couldn't fail this course because of a jeopardized B-mine of Savage. I got a C-plus in physics. That's the only C-plus I got.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:57.000
I got the rest of the B-minuses in A-s and so on. But it was my wardeloo.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:12.000
So my teachers helped me do this.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:15.000
Did you maintain contact with your parents?

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:38.000
I'm going to say yes when I... I don't know what the economy was, but I'm trying to remember...

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:45.000
I think that Mrs. Lippincott died at some point.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:24:07.000
And my father stayed on as a caretaker of the place. But my mother took a job in Westchester County, New York, and she would come back home about twice a month.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:19.000
But when I was in Columbia, she would be in New York on her days off. I would be able to see her, one of the more touching things I remember.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:30.000
I was always working, I worked at the dining hall tables for food and then extra money.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:40.000
There used to be a chain similar to Starbucks. Only Starbucks would probably be offended if I could say the chain was called Nidix.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:53.000
There was a Nidix hotdog. If anybody talks about Nidix, it's like Nathan's Frankfurt. You date yourself. You date yourself and tell you what part of the country you grew up in.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:25:03.000
So I worked at a Nidix on 42nd Street in Leckington Avenue. One day I worked at my home. I look up and there's my mother sitting at the counter.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:13.000
She came down to see me and so forth and worked. Very...

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:19.000
I was moving. Now I'm going to tell you something that probably...

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:30.000
I would say that it's the education I got at, the Catholic boarding school, Cornwells Heights, it was called, in eastern...

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:36.000
Cornwell's Pennsylvania. It was in eastern EAST, ERN, geographically, Pennsylvania.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:48.000
I would say being at that school and then going to Columbia, and even before I got to Columbia,

00:25:48.000 --> 00:26:01.000
being an accomplished... becoming an accomplished clarinetist, you know, filled in gave me some sense of confidence, you know,

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:11.000
because I was the first clarinetist in our... in the orchestra and first clarinetist in the band, and then the singular achievement at that time they had the...

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:24.000
the state of New Jersey hit, a New Jersey All-State orchestra, which you auditioned for. And in my senior year I was the first clarinetist for the, you know, for a room.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:34.000
Now there's some funny, there's some humorous little side stories. I learned to play jazz and it was a theater in New York called the The Earle Theatre.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:44.000
That was like the Apollo Theater in New York. And the The Earle Theatre used to have amateur hour. And, you know, what happens?

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:55.000
You go in for one ticket, you see a movie and you see a live stage show. And then they turned the lights out because they have to turn out.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:27:01.000
They want to get a hold on you couldn't... you couldn't sit through for a whole nother show, you know.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:07.000
And once a week they had what in effect was an amateur hour.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:16.000
So, you know, I would come very good. I was a very good classical clarinetist and was moving pretty good to become a little jazz.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:33.000
So I'm on this amateur hour competition. And as a white guy there, an Italian guy from Philadelphia, he was unbelievable on the clarinet.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:40.000
I mean, he was just unbelievable. About a year and a half older than me. His name was Buddy DeFranco.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:48.000
I mean, when I heard him play as I said, I mean, I was good. Now Buddy DeFranco and I became friends thereafter.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:55.000
I mean, he was one of the great, he maybe still lived me. He's one of the great clarinetists of our time.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:10.000
Alright, but he was great. So, now, during that period of time, I went to Juilliard School of Music twice during those summers.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:21.000
The betraying is a classical clarinetist. There's a place at that time in New York called, it was called Manny's Music on 48th Street.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:33.000
48th of 46th, I think it was 48th Street. But Manny's had a tradition. I think it was on Wednesday or Thursday. I mean, it may have been Thursday, late afternoon.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:41.000
They had a tradition of having musicians. It was a music store. It sold musical instruments principally at the principal.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:50.000
At that time, the instruments were trumpets, saxophone, clarinet, trombones, and so forth. It wasn't like... They had guitars,

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:58.000
but it wasn't like flutterwood guns, dominant things, where the reeds, the trumpets, the trombones, the clarinet, some saxophones.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:05.000
And I used to go and have my clarinet service there, you know, when I was there. And I got to know many the only.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:14.000
It took to me like, it's just something he... He just liked me as a young, you know, the Negro clarinetist.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:30.000
I think he also liked the fact that I was a classical clarinetist trained. And I, and so... And I learned a little bit jazz. He says, well, one day, he says, you know, he says, you know, Charlie Parker Charlie Barker's here.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:36.000
He's playing upstairs. I told Charlie Parker about you. I said, yeah, what would you tell him? I said, you know, you're very talented and so forth.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:42.000
He's there upstairs playing now. Why don't you go up? I said, no, I said, yeah, I'd like to go up so forth, you know.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:53.000
And so my clarinet was being fixed and so forth and so forth. So I go up and I'm listening and I'm very shy. And then many comes up having done what he had done to my clarinet.

00:29:53.000 --> 00:30:05.000
He had put it together in the box and so forth and so forth. And so Charlie Parker says to me, yeah, he told me, he says, you got your axe? And I said, yeah, he says, well, just said, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:12.000
I can't do that. No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, you put that thing together, boy. Put that thing together. And I'm shaking.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:15.000
I'm shaking.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:29.000
And he's playing and so forth. He says, well, what are you? What's your favorite? And I just said, well, you know, I can't. I said, I said, Mr. Parker, don't call me Parker. Call me Charlie Parker.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:42.000
I said, I said, you know, you just play along and I'll just sit and so forth. And then, and then as I got into it, I said, well, do you know, way back home in Indiana?

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:49.000
He said, yeah, I know. I'm in the end of a case. So forth. So, and he played way back home and then sunny side in the street and so forth.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:31:01.000
And I was sitting there, it sort of, you know, uncomfortably getting his custom. And then when he switched and played way back home in Indiana, which was the fastest of tempo, sunny side in the street.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:08.000
They're playing and playing and I'm playing along with him. And he's looking at me and he goes to me like that. And I said, oh, my God.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:14.000
Well, I'm frozen there. The best I could do was improvise. Okay.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:22.000
The only thing is like, this is like an author boy being an author boy for the Pope. You know, you know, do that.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:37.000
But I, but it gave me, I did what I had to do, you know, and then of course, like any, like any comforting, caring, elder, you know.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:44.000
He said, you're on your way, boy, you're on your way, you're on your way, you're on your way. I mean, you know, it was encouraging me.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:54.000
The man was an unbelievable genius. We could have an interview just about Charlie Parker, but I want to, I want to say this about Charlie Parker.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:32:04.000
Those people who may not be musicians who will see this, you have to understand what Charlie Parker could do is that there would be a melodic line.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:24.000
And Charlie Parker had the capacity of improvising within the melodic line. He would improvise so that you could hear the line, but the improvisation would be so extraordinary.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:32.000
The classic example is April and Paris. Okay. You listen to that's what he did. You know, I mean, to bring it.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:47.000
So, so that had a profound, that had a profound effect on me. But when I was in college, I had to make a, I had to make a decision. I couldn't, I couldn't practice a little.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:33:10.000
So, in the great pressure to do well, I played the sports because I just, it was in my system. But the most profound event that occurred in my life occurred during when I was in college,

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:38.000
shaped me to be very much who I am today. And that event was this. It was the beginning of my junior year. It was in January. I was taking midterm examinations.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:54.000
And while I'm taking midterm examinations, the proctor comes in and says, are you Clarence Jones? And I said, yes, I am. He said, well, there is an emergency call for you. You need to go to the dean's office.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:34:20.000
Now, ironically, I was taking this midterm examination on my birthday, January 8th, 1952. I go to the dean's office and I said, Mr. Jones, we got a call from the hospital in Camden, New Jersey.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:37.000
Cooper's hospital, I mean, Cooper's something hospital, and I said, yes, apparently, we don't know the details, which are mothers in the hospital. You need to call this number immediately.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:56.000
So, you know, I'm trying to decide. So I call, I said, essentially, my father was so broken up, he was a really difficult, he was a communicator, a doctor got on the phone and said,

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:21.000
we, your mother, we just operate on your mother. And we had to ask your father's consent. They had to take her a bowel track out, do a coloscopy in a bag, because she has cancer in her rectum.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:45.000
A abdominal rectal cancer, and she probably has about three or four months to live. I mean, I'm, so I, I go back and I say to the proctor, it was an S, I said,

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:56.000
I, I want to try to see if I can send 15 minutes to try to finish where I am in the exam. So I finished and it in my paper.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:36:14.000
And I went to, got on the bus, or go to the hospital. And it was, it was just, all this was a shock to me. My father was just in, in, in, in, in, consultable grief.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:38.000
So, we bring my mother home, in the hospital. When I talk to the doctor, and I'm talking to my mother. And she is very upset that I am there.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:54.000
That she, she was started to cry, why are you here? You should be in school. I said, well, my mother, her and so forth. She said, no, no, no, no, mom is going to be alright. You've got to go back to school. So I mean, I talked to the doctor.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:37:07.000
And, and he says, well, Mr. Jones, this is what it is. You know, I went in to see the dean of college.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:14.000
And my attitude was, you know, I can always get an education.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:28.000
This is, this is, this is my mother, you know. So I wanted to, I wanted to take a leave of absence. I wanted to drop out, take a leave of absence. He says, no, I don't think you need to do that clearance.

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:37.000
Why don't we work out something where you just, you just stay. And we'll work out something with your classes, you know, you try to keep up.

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:59.000
And I had some friends and so, so what I did was that I, I stayed in school. But I set up, I put a, I put a desk at the foot of my mother's bed in her bedroom. And I swear I did all my homework.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:17.000
And I had to leave periodically to go back to New York. I also had to leave to keep some credibility with her because she refused to believe that in fact I had permission to study. She just refused to believe that she would cry.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:22.000
You know, Mama, what you're going to have an education is an education. Okay.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:35.000
May 4th, 1952 she dies. She's buried on May 8th.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:55.000
When they, she was 160 pounds about, tall, five foot, 10, 155, 60 pounds.

00:38:55.000 --> 00:39:08.000
She died. She was about 99 pounds, less than 99 pounds. They took her body out from the mattress and took her to the undertaker place.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:27.000
And when they removed her body and they were removing the bed things, you know, I saw that there was a letter under the mattress that she had written to me.

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:43.000
All during the time she was six, she was carrying on this charade. And Mama's going to get better. Mama's going to get better. You know, she's going to be, not going to be as different.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:51.000
I'm going to have to get adjusted to doing things. But Mama's going to get better. We're going to get better. She was losing more weight anyway.

00:39:51.000 --> 00:40:06.000
So she leaves this letter to me. And the essence of the letter is that she's apologizing to me. She's asking, my forgiveness for leaving me.

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:27.000
She's asking, my forgiveness. And she's talking about how proud I have made her feel that no mother, she says, could ask for a son that could bring her great joy.

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:47.000
And then my favorite, she was a cook, one of the best cooks in the world. And she, I was a dessert, you know, how I'm so to speak. And so she knew that the things that she homemade for me were crullers and a dessert called floating island.

00:40:48.000 --> 00:41:10.000
And she says, she says, I'm Mama's sorry she can't be here to make crullers and floating island. But I wrote the recipe down for you. And I'm sorry to leave you, but you know, I know that someday you're going to be a great man.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:23.000
I know you're going to be a great man and always try to be good and always try to make me proud because I know I am so proud of you. And someday you're going to be a great man.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:30.000
I'm sorry I have to leave you. Please forgive me.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:42.000
Okay. Well, let me tell you something. I was an only child, I know your brother's sister.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:59.000
I spent a limited amount of time with my parents. But as I begin going forward in my life and I measured things in terms of how difficult they were or how painful they were.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:12.000
It became very clear that my internal gyroscope was founded on the following.

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:27.000
I had been to the apex and the mountaintop of pain. I couldn't conceive of anything happening in my life thereafter.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:40.000
I couldn't conceive of anything thereafter, having a more profound effect of loss in anguish and the loss of my mother.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:43:03.000
So, when I would study and read the political history of China, and I would see that Chou and Lai, when a great China's political leader says the strongest steel, is tempered by the hottest fire.

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:17.000
I knew what he was saying. It also conditioned me to have the dialectic of compassion and strength.

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:34.000
Okay. So, that for example, the Korean War broke out in June 25th, 1950. I was a student.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:46.000
As a student, I was entitled to a student deferment.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:44:09.000
Because in the aftermath of my mother's death, in 52, I was scheduled to graduate in 53, because in order to sustain, maintain your exemption, your student deferment, either had to graduate or you had to be full-time in school.

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:16.000
And if you were a nearing graduation, you had to have made an application to a graduate school.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:29.000
Okay. And if you didn't have either of those things, you were not entitled to exempt me, exempt from the job.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:50.000
So, my job board snatched me, because I was in the space. I was drafted in August 12th, 1953.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:45:08.000
I was angry. I had also become politicized in college.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:20.000
I had also met in New York to my uncle, an extraordinary man, who I didn't even know who he was.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:27.000
I heard you, I saw him and went to see him in a Broadway play, but then I found that he was an actor with Paul Robeson.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:36.000
I went to see him in Othello or on Whitman Avenue or something. I went to see him in something with Uta Hagen on Broadway.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:47.000
And my uncle had become friends with him. And when I was in Columbia, I had two instances with Paul Robson.

00:45:47.000 --> 00:46:02.000
I had been active politically in college. This is before my mother died in 1952, but that whole area between 1949 and 1952 had been active and so forth.

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:13.000
And I loved football in addition to all the other things. But if you loved football, you either played football in Baker's Field as a part of the Columbia team,

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:24.000
or if you went to a football game, and I was not varsity, but I was in line with the varsity team.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:32.000
So I would go to every football team, every Saturday, I'd be up at Baker's Field at Columbia, New York.

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:41.000
And my classmates who were more politically inclined would say, well, you know, when we have to hand out leaflets, you never hand out any leaflets, you're never there.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:54.000
You're never there, you know, you need a committee and I commit it. So I told Paul Robeson this story once I was so I'm socially with my uncle Leda, party, and I told him that story.

00:46:54.000 --> 00:47:12.000
He was tall and big, and he says, you know, you go back and you tell your white, liberal progressive friends, I have lots of white progressive friends,

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:33.000
but you go back and tell your white progressive friends who are students, that one touchdown on a Saturday afternoon by you, a Negro in Baker's Field with that stadium filled with almost 50,000 people.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:48.000
One touchdown have greater impact on getting white people to understand the equality of Negroes than anything they could ever write in those leaflets.

00:47:48.000 --> 00:48:03.000
And I was like, this is for us, never would we get that. The other instance that influenced on me is that he at this time was being summoned before the House of American Activities Committee.

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:09.000
And I watched him on television.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:26.000
So let me just, let me just, you go back and look at the archives, I would suggest you go back and look at Paul Robeson appearing before the House Internal Security Committee, the House on American Communities Committee, but it was chaired by James Eastland from Mississippi.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:40.000
And when Paul Robeson was being asked, the sit is sworn in as a witness by the chairman, he stands up for six foot, four or six foot, he says, you, he points his finger at him.

00:48:40.000 --> 00:49:01.000
You Mr. Wieslin, you are unconstitutionally seated in that chair. You don't have the authority, the constitutional hourly authority to ask me any questions whatsoever because you were illegally sitting in this Congress.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:18.000
You were illegally because of the mass exclusion of my people invoting. You have no authority whatsoever to ask me any questions. I said, wow, that was a bad dude.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:39.000
Okay, I mean it influenced me, okay. So my mother dies, influenced Paul Robeson, my anger, not getting exempted. So when I report the night before the induction, by the way, I had some left wing.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:50:02.000
I'm not going to say they were communist because I don't know that they were communist. It was the young, young friends of mine, but they were members of the Labor Youth League, which was supposed to have been a communist-affiliated organization, but they were left, but they were very, they were just great friends of mine.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:05.000
I had a...

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:12.000
What was the effect of inter-refuge for a second when you were talking about your friends that were illegal being it? Is this the same group or is this the same kind of politics there?

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:27.000
No, no, no, these were different. There were friends, they were an extended group. They weren't necessarily, the Paul Robeson comments were meant to my friends who, yes, I said, no matter if they were the same. They were substantially the same.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:35.000
But I had become friends with... And one woman by the name of Judith Treesman, Judy, I don't know whether you're alive, whether you have a...

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:44.000
Here, this is a seedest, but I had such admiration for her and her family treated me like I was just part of their family, great warmth.

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:54.000
And I remember Judy Treisman, I mean, that was where she was at the young woman at that time. I don't know where it is today, but at that time she says, you know,

00:50:55.000 --> 00:51:03.000
you know, you know, you don't want to go. If you don't want to report, you know, maybe you just think about it.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:12.000
If you want to go to Canada or if you don't want to go to Canada, I think you should go to Eastern Europe, Czechoslovakia and so forth like that.

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:19.000
No, no, no, no, and then she says, well, you know, she said, don't get the wrong idea. You know, I parents like you and I like you.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:26.000
And I mean, I really care about you. So all I'm simply saying, if you wanted to go and I said, I'd go with you, if I would make it easy for you.

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:31.000
You know, and I find something to do. And I said, what are you talking about? She says, yeah, I would do that.

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:39.000
You know, because I know you're hurting. I know you don't want to go. And I said, no, Judy, I can't do that. But I seriously thought about it.

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:48.000
I seriously thought about it. But as a result of the anger of being inductive and I didn't think I should have been inducted,

00:51:48.000 --> 00:52:08.000
in my draft board in Mount Holly, New Jersey, I signed from Richard Vilariani, who was a news, who went to Burlington, high school in Burlington, New Jersey.

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:29.000
There were very few college students. And I still did this day believe that this this this prejudice in Manholy draft board saying, well, we'll send this Negro, you know, draft them, who's they think he is.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:38.000
I mean, I think if I think I had been white, I wouldn't think I'd have been drafted. I think I just said, oh, he's a role to Columbia College.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:46.000
And yes, he had a problem with this. I don't think that a draft of me has mother died. No, they didn't. They didn't care. So I was bitter.

00:52:46.000 --> 00:53:02.000
So the night before I was to report for induction, I sat down and wrote a handwritten note as to why I was reporting for induction, but why I was not going to serve in the Army.

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:19.000
And I in the course of the note, I said, in effect, I said, I'm willing to go and serve and and and give my life for my country as a member of the United States Army.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:33.000
When my country cheese me as a first class citizen, I'm not willing to put my life on the line in a war that I have lots of questions about the Korean War, lots of questions, but I'm not willing to do that.

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:52.000
And so therefore I'm reporting for induction and I cited the first. I wasn't a lawyer. I don't know anything. I mean, I was educated or being excited the first, the fifth, the 14th and 15th of members of the Constitution.

00:53:53.000 --> 00:54:18.000
As a reason I was not. So I'm in Whitehall Street, New York. I report for duty August 13th early in the morning. Now, have you seen some of these military pictures? When you report to duty, the first thing the non-commissioned officer says, and it was a Negro, non-commissioned officer, he says, all right, Cece, okay.

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:32.000
You raise your hand, you know, you're being inducted to the Army. Well, I didn't raise my hand, you know, because I figured if I didn't, if I didn't consent to this, they couldn't, so I didn't raise my hand.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:45.000
So I'm listening to all this ramp about, you know, your ass is grass now, you know, you're in the Army, you belong to us.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:59.000
And then Sergeant, he says, well, what's with you? What's with you soldier? And I said, there's nothing, I just, I said, I'm here when reporting.

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:13.000
What are you some kind of cook or conscientious objective? And I said, no. And then I gave him a statement to read. And he read it, he said, what are you some kind of commie? I said, no. He said, well, get out of line.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:23.000
So he puts me out of line. And then they, they, a captain, a white captain officer comes over and so what's the problem?

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:39.000
Private Jones, what's the problem with Mr. Jones, he said. I said, well, I realize I'm here because I want to show up. But I don't, these are my reasons why I don't want to serve sir.

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:50.000
I don't think I think I'm being unfairly treated and I want to serve you, read it. And that's when he says, oh, he said, we better come over here.

00:55:50.000 --> 00:56:05.000
And they had some kind of conference for about two or three, but two hours. Whatever they decided, oh, yeah, whatever they decided you go, they were going to put me on the bus to Fort Dix.

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:17.000
So I go to Fort Dix. And somebody at Fort Dix had been alerted that I was on the bus and coming. Now, in the Fort Dix, that's when they, that's when it gets serious.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:33.000
Because that's when they want you to sign up for your, your insurance, you sign, you're going to get paid, the issue your clothes, you know, you, you, and so they kept saying, you know, you know, sign this, you know, you're not going to get any money.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:48.000
I said, I don't care. I'm not signing anything. What? Well, if you can't sign, you're not going to have any insurance. You're not going to, you're not going to get any paycheck. You're not going to get anything. I said, I don't care. I'm not signing anything.

00:56:48.000 --> 00:57:07.000
So they issue me, they issue me standard things, they put me and they process me to go for basic training. But no, stop there. Before they process me, I take, I take examinations, okay, placement examination.

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:21.000
Don't do so. So about three or four days after I take the placement examination, I find that they're putting me in a group that scheduled to go to some place in Maryland.

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:34.000
Because we're going to be part of some special forces team, so special forces intelligence team. So I said, I think there must be some mistake.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:56.000
So I remember going to one of these two orientation things. I'm listening. And I'm talking about how they're going to, we're going to be trained as going to the special unit. Some of us may go to California to the Army language school to learn Russian or Polish, principally that.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:07.000
I'm thinking to myself and then I put it all together. Because I talked to some of the other soldiers who were all gone ho about this. They're going to send you to Fort Jackson to Parachupir School and so forth.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:24.000
The bottom line is that they were being trained to be special ops who would jump at night behind me in lines in a Soviet Union and pull on the Czechoslovakia. So I said, so I'm laughing while I find out I said, now, this is after they go to the Army language school.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:39.000
So I said, now, now let's assume that I go through all this and I'm fluent in Russian. How am I going to explain this black face of mine as I show up in the Russian countryside, the Polish countryside? I said, this is crazy. It's crazy.

00:58:39.000 --> 00:59:06.000
I mean, that's on saying the military was at the point. But anyway, so I, I, I mean, the whole of it and I was bitter, angry over the death of my mother and really, and really, I really began to, I was influenced by Paul Rupsen and I figured I, you know, and, and I also trying to find a way of getting out. I'm not doing it.

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:24.000
I just wanted to ask, this is a good time, I think, to ask, what other influences beyond Rupsen? I mean, with the people that you were reading, had, had looking back, you know, this is a very device. What do you think inspired us?

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:47.000
I think my friends, I had become, I had become, I become friends with a lot of New York student leftists who had become, in one case, a couple of cases had become very dear friends of mine.

00:59:48.000 --> 01:00:06.000
In one case, I can think of as a poet by the name of Robert Barron Nemiroff. Robert Nemiroff was getting a master's degree in English from NYU. We became, he even got a Columbia, he went to NYU.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:24.000
And we became friendly through our, my political activities in New York. And Robert's family owned a restaurant, an Israeli restaurant, on 48, 46th street in Manhattan called the Habibi Restaurant.

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:48.000
And it was, it was a nightclub, Mr. Ron. And, and Robert introduced me to his parents, particularly his mother. And when his mother found out that I was at Columbia, that I was working on tables and she, and I was skinny. And she says, well, speaking in Newtish, she spoke very little English.

01:00:49.000 --> 01:01:00.000
And, and so Bobby would be talking to her and Yiddish and talking to me in English. Which by the way, as a result of that relationship, three or four or five years of knowing her, I was fairly

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:21.000
capable and conversational Yiddish. Particularly when it came to food, you know, I used to, people, I would say, people say, well, how do you know anything about Canadian lock? I said, I know Canadian lock a multiple, I know it because I used to have it all the time.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:42.000
And, and anyway, they had this, this nightclub. And, and she would have me come down and eat outside the kitchen, right to the entrance of the kitchen to the nightclub where they would have the restaurant part. I would come anytime. And then I wouldn't do it except maybe on the weekends.

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:56.000
Weekends, I'd come there, weekends before. But anyway, I became very, very close to Robert B. Nemiroff, he and I became friends. And he ended up marrying Lorraine Hansberry, the playwright, who also became a friend of mine when I was in school.

01:01:56.000 --> 01:02:11.000
Lorraine Hansberry was an African American playwright from Chicago, became good friends of mine. She married Robert B. Nemiroff. And the other good friend of mine were the Art D'Lugoff + Burt D'Lugoff brothers.

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:24.000
Art D'Lugoff was an entrepreneur and owned the village gate, nightclub, and his brother, Bert, owned the nightclub with him except Bert went to medical school to John Hopkins.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:37.000
So, while, while Art was running the nightclub, Bert was in medical school to John Hopkins. But those were, those were my good friends.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:47.000
And then, you know, I go through the military experience.

01:02:53.000 --> 01:03:06.000
I've become friendly. But first of all, there are a couple of people in the military that when they found out these all, oh, this is 19, I mean in military in 1953, it's a 55, okay.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:17.000
The military only be segregated beginning in 1950, okay. The executive order late 1940 number, Harry Truman. So only had an integrated army for three years.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:32.000
So I was in company D, 47th Regiment, in Fort Dix. And I just remembered being about, I don't know.

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:43.000
Maybe it was, maybe it was 40% black, maybe it was about 40% black or more.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:58.000
So, I had a company commander who was from Mississippi, Captain, and non-commissioned offices were virtually all Negro at that time.

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:10.000
So, I'm in the military and I become very, very close friends.

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:25.000
One, one word spreads that I'm going to be here indefinitely or more specifically, I am not going to be shipped overseas after basic training.

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:37.000
Guys came coming up the men said, well, tell me how you did this. Because they wanted to revoke. They didn't, they wanted to be in a holdover status. They didn't want to be shipped out.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:49.000
And the only way you could get a discharge in the army is a dishonable discharge, a section 8 being crazy or an undesirable. So all of them wanted to be a section 8 crazy.

01:04:49.000 --> 01:05:02.000
I had a good friend of mine who says, oh, I'm a communist. I said, well, this name was fields. I said, I'm not a communist. Well, no, but then they won't say, I'm going to go back and told them, I mean, I didn't even look at that thing. I signed that law of the youth.

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:31.000
I didn't sign the law of the youth. I didn't make that clear to you. When I handed my statement, I also, as part of the various series of papers you signed consenting to being in the army, there's a whole lot of papers but attaches those papers where a list was a lawyer for 400 organizations that the then attorney general, a graph of Herbert Brownell determined was on either communist or communist front organizations.

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:41.000
Including a lot of, I mean, organizations, I knew in that communist. The young progressives of America, they were not a communist organization, but they were there.

01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:45.000
And so I didn't sign it.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:56.000
So word spread that I had not signed it. And so some of the soldiers are saying, we don't know whether, you know, what you are not. And in the other word, spread.

01:05:56.000 --> 01:06:11.000
And so it's like being in the military is a little bit like prison, you know. Words spread that I had to somebody said to be careful because the words said to somebody, I needed to be taken into a shower and taught a lesson in loyalty.

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:15.000
So you better watch yourself.

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:29.000
And when I developed a very good friendship with a guy, was a big guy like a football player. He became very close friends. He was somewhat protective of me too.

01:06:29.000 --> 01:06:42.000
His last name was Hinton. Big guy. Very good friends. Fast forward.

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:55.000
I'm sitting in a bar somewhere in Harlem on leave, talking to Clint. We're drinking, trying to see what girls are going to get so far.

01:06:55.000 --> 01:07:11.000
And he starts to cry. So I think it's too much liquor. You know, you know, we started crying. You know, it had a lot of, a lot to drink, a lot of beers. So I had to cry.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:34.000
And then he told me, he said, I had treated him like a brother. I had taken him to my family and he is, he is so sorry. I said, what are you sorry about? He says, you know, my main job here in this, in your platoon is to report about you.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:49.000
I said, what do you mean you've put about me? He said, I have to write reports about you. I said, what kind of reports? Well, you know, whether you've ever said anything against the United States, whether, whether you're a communist.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:56.000
And I said, well, the only thing he likes is sports and girls. You know, sports and women, that's all he talks about.

01:07:56.000 --> 01:08:10.000
And you've introduced me to some of your good friends and so forth. And he had a lot to drink. And he just unburdened. And I said, I can't.

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:17.000
So that was over a weekend, right?

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:28.000
I go back, we go back to camp on the fourth of formation on Monday. Monday afternoon and Monday evening, I'm looking for a hit and he's gone.

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:38.000
I never saw him again. I never saw him again. I'm in the army for 21 months.

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:45.000
And where did he serve the war? Fort Dex. That's Fort Dex for 24 months.

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:59.000
I was trained into telecommunications, army, signal communications, teaching the media intricacies of how to operate signal equipment on the field and so forth.

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:13.000
So I went to the whole basic training. I went through everything and you go, Divwack, you know, marches for 26 par. I did the whole thing.

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:27.000
But 21 months, I'm in my barracks one morning, getting ready to go to what I normally do.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:38.000
And an MP comes in, two MPs come in. And one MP says, are you private Jones? They yes. They had me this paper.

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:45.000
And it's a, they had me this paper and in a sense it's like a summons and complaint.

01:09:45.000 --> 01:10:03.000
It's a notice that they're bringing me up for court marshaling me as a security risk with this whole series of allegations.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:16.000
So one allegation being that I had refused to sign the loyalty of the other allegation being that since 1938 up until the present I'm a member of the Communist Party.

01:10:16.000 --> 01:10:21.000
Well, of course I was only seven years old in 1938.

01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:45.000
The other was that I had lived, which is true. After, after my mother died, my last year in college, and one I had lived in a housing development.

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:56.000
One by the I.O. International labor union, one of the labor unions that was deemed to be a communist front-leab you that I lived there. That's where I lived.

01:10:56.000 --> 01:11:03.000
And the other was that I had maintained a very close friend, which was true.

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:15.000
And the doctor who was still today, he's retired or doctorate at the Stanford University, who at the time had been a vice president of the International Union of Students.

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:26.000
Been a member of the Communist Party since I was eight. Didn't sign a loyalty of, lived in the Allerton Avenue houses and the Bronx.

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:42.000
And so I'm assigned a council, the Bence Council, and they have this steel board of inquiry at Fort Dix.

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:57.000
And my commanding officer is called. And so I'm the principal evidence they put in, or the allegations.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:12:06.000
And we both the allegations, they said, well, not a member of the Communist Party. Yes, it is true. He did live there. Yes, it is true. He knows so and so. Yes, it is true.

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:17.000
He didn't sign the loyalty of, and even my, Judge Advocate General lawyer said, well, these are all, you're, you're, you're.

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:25.000
He put my commanding officer on the stand. They said to testify to whether I was a good soldier.

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:36.000
Bottom line, if you could have clearance zone in your company, he said, he was the number one soldier of the honor to have him serve an anytime, never heard him, nothing could get glowing remarks.

01:12:36.000 --> 01:12:45.000
Plus, I had been chosen as soldier of the month. And soldier of the month, let me tell you, I get, I become soldier of the month.

01:12:46.000 --> 01:13:01.000
I become soldier of the month for the 47th regiment, something for tie in the way soldier of the month is that you, you stand before your footlocker and your need is closed and your footlocker is in perfect shape and your bed is made so they put a quarter or something and it's so for you.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:13.000
Shoes are shine. And then you're asked to take your disassemble your M-1 rifle. Okay. And reassemble that. Blindfold it. Okay.

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:35.000
I did that and got a perfect score. And so as a result of that, I was given the good conduct metal. So I was, I was chosen as soldier of the month, given a good conduct metal and a special three day leave and all this is in the record when I'm being courtmorshaw.

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:56.000
The verdict comes down the very next day. I've been found the undesirable national security was to the United States government and to the United States military.

01:13:57.000 --> 01:14:18.000
At which point two M poos came took me back to my barracks. They supervised me packing up all of my things, put me in a duffle bag, put me in a jeep with a one way ticket to Port Authority.

01:14:18.000 --> 01:14:31.000
And they waited until the bus they put me on it. They escorted me to the exits, the gate of fort fort dicks under arm guard and put me on the bus under arm guard.

01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:47.000
I was given an undesirable discharge on August 13th, 1955. I think it was August 14th. I think I was inducted on August 13th, but I was returned on August 14th.

01:14:48.000 --> 01:15:02.000
So as I'm riding in on the bus, I'm smouldering and I'm thinking they don't know what they got their hands.

01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:14.000
So I go and I'm staying with my uncle. I discuss it with my uncle. My uncle says, well I think you got to go see the American Civil Liberties Union.

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:23.000
So I go down to the American Civil Liberties Union. I tell them my story and they have me meet with a lawyer by the name of Stanley Faulkner, God rest his soul.

01:15:23.000 --> 01:15:35.000
Stanley Faulkner, we filed an appeal. It was the first time I went, the first time I went into the Pentagon.

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:47.000
The Pentagon has something called the Army Discharge Review Board. The Army Discharge Review Board, the Armed Services Discharge Review Board.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:16:02.000
It's consistent like the Supreme Court, all of the uniformed services are sitting in bunk, you know, the Navy, the Marines, the Coast Guard, the Air Force are all sitting there. Military officers.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:11.000
And it's like the Court of Appeals. Excuse me, I need to go to the men's room. Take a break.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:28.000
So I said, I said, so I went to Stanley Faulkner and it's like an appeal. And, and he subpoenaed and my military commander and everything was there to make a long story short as a result of the appeal.

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:45.000
They handed me, they awarded me a general discharge. They moved up my discharge one notch. Stanley Faulkner says, no, that's not satisfactory. He's entitled to an unrupl discharge.

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:56.000
And I, and I hadn't, I wasn't thinking about what I was, what I was going to do, but I decided I wanted to go to law school at that time.

01:16:56.000 --> 01:17:10.000
And I, I considered, I went to Columbia College and I was considering about making, I went and went up to talk to Columbia Law School and I told them the problem I had.

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:26.000
They didn't even get to the question whether, and grades and applications and so forth. They discouraged me because they said that, why you have this problem, I think you ought to get this problem solved before you consider me enter law school, you don't know.

01:17:26.000 --> 01:17:33.000
You know, you're not going to be able to be a lawyer if you'd have this thing hanging over you.

01:17:33.000 --> 01:17:46.000
Meanwhile, I had become friendly with the judge, he would delay me and some other lawyers and they suggested I go and talk to Boston University Law School.

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:56.000
So I talked to Boston University Law School and I told them the issue and they said, well, listen, if you want a legal education, you can just, you know, you will give your legal education.

01:17:56.000 --> 01:18:03.000
You will decide whether you're going to ever practice, but you will admit you, you know, you get your papers.

01:18:03.000 --> 01:18:13.000
The mere fact that this is, that you have currently an undesirable discharge has been general and you don't know how it's going to appeal, that's not going to stop you.

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:16.000
So you're welcome to come.

01:18:16.000 --> 01:18:23.000
I keep thinking, of course, I need an honorable discharge because as an honorable discharge, I'd qualify for the Korean Conflict GI Bill.

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:34.000
Okay? So Stanley Faulkner, we sued, he brought a rid of mandamus, I believe.

01:18:34.000 --> 01:18:45.000
A rid of mandamus for those people who met for me, it's a, it's an administrative proceeding that's brought against an officer of the government agency.

01:18:45.000 --> 01:18:56.000
To compel that person, to perform the duties that he is, or she is required to do according to the statute.

01:18:56.000 --> 01:19:14.000
So Stanley Faulkner's thesis was that the Secretary of the Army, he had a constitutional, he was compelled by the nature of the party to issue me an honorable discharge.

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:21.000
Okay? I'm at Boston University Law School.

01:19:21.000 --> 01:19:41.000
I'm registering, knowing full well, but maybe I'll win the case and maybe I won't win the case, but Boston, they're already working out a situation where if I could come up with just a modest little amount for the down payment, they'll carry me and so forth, and they're working at the best of region they could.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:48.000
I haven't completed registering in law school, hadn't gotten my books.

01:19:48.000 --> 01:20:01.000
When I got this urgent message to call Stanley Faulkner, I call Stanley Faulkner, and he said, we won, you've just been issued an honorable discharge.

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:19.000
And this is what you must tell me. You must, I'm going to get in touch with the Veterans Administration Officer in Boston and tell them that we're going to have your copy of your order, so forth, so that you can get your benefits.

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:29.000
That's what happened. Is that the Veterans Administration was notified, I had an honorable discharge, the VA then notified the Berzer at Boston University,

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:38.000
and they then activated me as being going to school and getting my tuition in the Korean Conflict GI Bill, and low in behold.

01:20:38.000 --> 01:20:50.000
I got a check for, I don't know, several thousand dollars, maybe about 12 thousand, maybe I don't know, 13 thousand or something, for all the back pay, all the back pay which I didn't get military.

01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:56.000
I didn't get any pay, paycheck, that will time.

01:20:56.000 --> 01:21:14.000
But I introduced this by talking about the death of my mother, because her death made me fearless.

01:21:14.000 --> 01:21:23.000
I didn't have any brothers and sisters, I didn't have any brothers and sisters to comfort me.

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:29.000
Okay?

01:21:29.000 --> 01:21:53.000
I became very clear to me that we are all, to a large extent, the challenges to what extent can you control your own destiny and not have it determined by a third party.

01:21:53.000 --> 01:22:01.000
And what are you prepared to put at risk? What are you prepared?

01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:13.000
Now, my attitude, I lost my mother, I didn't feel like I could lose anything. I wasn't afraid of anything.

01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:39.000
I was angry. And during the period, I go to the New York Public Library the day after I get into New York, and I'm saying at my uncle's place and he's telling me to go down.

01:22:39.000 --> 01:22:47.000
I go to the New York Public Library because I was trying to decide what I'm going to do and go into the library, be paper and stuff.

01:22:47.000 --> 01:22:53.000
And I hear somebody call my name. I don't know if it's a call my name.

01:22:53.000 --> 01:23:03.000
Clarence Jones is not you, Clarence Jones, I turn around. And as a woman, and I had seen this woman in like five years.

01:23:03.000 --> 01:23:22.000
And she was Ann Norton. Ann Norton had gone to Sarah Lawrence. And when I was at Columbia, occasionally a group of guys from Columbia would go up and party at Sarah Lawrence.

01:23:22.000 --> 01:23:34.000
And Sarah Lawrence, at that time, the women lived in houses, different houses. So it was a big thing to be able to go on a Saturday night to go to Sarah Lawrence because that's where you had all these girls.

01:23:34.000 --> 01:23:52.000
And Norton was, they had parties and I knew her. She was white. And I knew she would, you know, she was one of those active progressive, very nice people.

01:23:52.000 --> 01:24:08.000
And last thing I heard, she was living in Chicago, working for Spiegel's and so forth. No, no, she's in New York now working for the American National Theatre Company. What's that? What's, you know, an American National Theatre Company? What are you doing? What are you doing? What are you doing?

01:24:08.000 --> 01:24:23.000
I was talking, and I just told, I told the story about what happened to me in the Army. She's, oh my God, well, where are you staying? I'm staying with my uncle. And she says, this is, I never will be, she says, well, what are you doing tomorrow?

01:24:23.000 --> 01:24:32.000
I said, I don't know what I'm doing. I'm doing, what I'm doing tomorrow, she says, well, you know, the American National Theatre is having our annual thing on Broadway.

01:24:32.000 --> 01:24:44.000
Would you like to come? You know, you've been in the Army, would you like to come? Being a good boy, I said, sure. So I go to the American National Theatre Company's production of Damn Yankees, okay?

01:24:44.000 --> 01:25:01.000
Gwen Verden, okay? It was a second Broadway play I'd ever seen. The first had been with my uncle when I had seen Paul Roveson. Maybe it was on Whitman, I had something with you to hug. And I was the second time, okay?

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:10.000
But this time, I mean, I had good seats there with Paul Robeson with you to hug. But this time I'm with Antony and I get the very great seats.

01:25:10.000 --> 01:25:21.000
And I didn't have a tuxedo. My uncle and I are about the same size. So I had to go and borrow his dark blue suit.

01:25:21.000 --> 01:25:35.000
And I wore a bow tie, a black bow tie and a white shirt and a dark blue suit. And I wear and a pair of his dark shoes, like shoes. I never knew. That's how I went to. And to wear my uncle's clothes.

01:25:35.000 --> 01:25:48.000
We went to Sardi's. She began with a friend of hers. This is all during the appeal process. And during the appeal process, she had to type up.

01:25:48.000 --> 01:26:04.000
I had to provide copies of the transcripts. It was for a lot of photocopying, so forth. So she and a woman friend of hers, they spent hours typing up my appeal transcript.

01:26:04.000 --> 01:26:27.000
And during that whole process, we became romantically involved. And then I married her. And that was a major turning point in my life.

01:26:27.000 --> 01:26:52.000
And so my father had remarried. I married one of my mother's best friends when I came to, I mean, I liked so forth. And so I let my father and my new stepmother know I was going to get married.

01:26:52.000 --> 01:27:09.000
And I had become friendly with a couple. Charles W. White and Fran Barrett White. Charles W. White was an artist. Very distinguished artist at UCLA at one point.

01:27:09.000 --> 01:27:30.000
One of the before Romare Bearden and Romare Bearden and one of the great artists. He was the best man at my wedding to Ann. And Fran Barrett was, I guess, the maid of honor to Ann.

01:27:30.000 --> 01:27:51.000
We were, we were getting very good friends. And my, my, my, my in laws, my wife's parents were reconciled. They were not, they were not unfriendly.

01:27:51.000 --> 01:28:11.000
They were sort of matter of fact, protocol friendly, you know, but not hostile in any way. They were at the wedding. We had a reception at the Belmont Hotel, a wedding cake and all of that.

01:28:11.000 --> 01:28:28.000
When Ann and I were dating, I learned, I mean, I knew it in general, but I didn't know the details. We got closer to it. I learned that yes, her parents had founded the WWE Northern publishing company. And Ann was in Northern, in Northern was because

01:28:28.000 --> 01:28:55.000
William Warder Norton founded the WWE Northern publishing company with her mother. And so she came from a publishing business. And that her father had died, her father had died when she was 18 and 19. Her mother remarries.

01:28:55.000 --> 01:29:15.000
Her mother remarries a banker, an international banker from Holland. His name is Daniel H. Crena de Iongh, C-R-E-N-E-A, small D-E, capital I-O-N-G-H.

01:29:15.000 --> 01:29:35.000
He was the head of the banking industry in the Netherlands, the number one bank of the Netherlands. He became, he was also one of the early, not one of the first treasuries of the World Bank.

01:29:35.000 --> 01:29:50.000
But affecting my relationship was not those, was that his very best friend in the world, whom he vacationed with and when he married Anne's mother, whom they vacationed with.

01:29:50.000 --> 01:30:19.000
In Johannesburg, South Africa was Hendrik Verwoerd, the architect of a part-time. My stepfather in law is the banker for not only the Netherlands, but is the banker for Heinrich Fairbold and that whole nationalist party.

01:30:20.000 --> 01:30:45.000
Now he treated me with protocol warmth and courtesy. It was something almost like out of Downton Abbey. I mean, it was like, it was like, he cheated me as a gentleman.

01:30:45.000 --> 01:31:07.000
There was no hostility toward me. It wasn't a question whether he approved or disapproved. He accepted as a fact. I was married to his wife's daughter and he treated me with great friendship initially and then it eventually became affection and respect.

01:31:07.000 --> 01:31:30.000
We had a kind of annual ritual. He was a member of the Netherlands Club in the somewhere near Rockefeller Center and every holiday he would take me to lunch at his Netherlands Club where other international bankers would be.

01:31:30.000 --> 01:31:48.000
He would probably introduce me as his son-in-law and the breakthrough in the relationship with my indoors came.

01:31:49.000 --> 01:32:12.000
When my wife's mother, who was a classical chamber music, violist, when her daughter had told me that I played the clarinet, suggested that I bring up my clarinet one weekend, not knowing what I could play.

01:32:12.000 --> 01:32:33.000
She heard me play warm up. The best thing I can tell you was that it blew her away because I sat down when she was just watching this thing. I said, why don't I play for you? The Mozart clarinet concerto in A for you to listen to you. You just sit over there and I'll play. She was stunned.

01:32:33.000 --> 01:33:02.000
The next week, this is in Wilton, Connecticut. The next week, she arranges for there to be a chamber music group in which her son-in-law is going to be the clarinetist in which we played Brahms, Mozart, but things for clarinet and strings and cello and flute are primarily written by Brahms and Mozart Beethoven writing some things.

01:33:03.000 --> 01:33:32.000
And then, of course, I would perform solo pieces like Flight of the Bumblebee. That single act made my mother alone go out of her way to tell other people about how she wanted them to meet me and how he's been able to play the piano.

01:33:33.000 --> 01:34:01.000
It was busy, but we want him to come up here every weekend because you have to see him and so forth as a person. And I write one of my books. I write one of my books when she heard me play the Mozart clarinet concerto. It was a whole. She heard me play this before we had any children because no one had children.

01:34:01.000 --> 01:34:13.000
Now, had you and Anne talked about what life might be like for you as an interracial couple at that time, or did you have other examples of couples that you knew?

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:27.000
Well, Charlie White was a black artist married to a white woman, a fan baron.

01:34:27.000 --> 01:34:44.000
And I say this, not in criticism. And went to the, and went to the The Brearley School, private girl school. She went to Sarah Lawrence and she was in high school. She was raised by a governess.

01:34:44.000 --> 01:35:05.000
In addition to having a home in Wilton, her parents had a townhouse on Gramercy Park. And at that time, everybody who owned a townhouse had a key to the park.

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:29.000
So I remember we lived in the head of the townhouse with 17 Gramercy Park. And Anne had a tremendous deep idealism, but also had a certain kind of

01:35:29.000 --> 01:35:49.000
sort of nutritionist, certain kind of attitude that she was certain she was right. The classic example, this is after we're living in Boston.

01:35:49.000 --> 01:36:13.000
My oldest daughter, the baby, was shopping at a food place and a check out. And Anne had to go back. So Tina Christine was in this little bassinet and we left her right up on the counter, you know, on the other checkout counter.

01:36:13.000 --> 01:36:37.000
And I was standing there by, and the checkout counter, I must have returned and somebody said, well, whose little baby is this? You know, not in a negative way. But my wife saw this. And like a lioness, you know, this is what I'm going to say.

01:36:37.000 --> 01:36:51.000
And her way of dealing with this. So she's, she's white, fair skin, blonde hair, gray blue eyes, attractive.

01:36:51.000 --> 01:37:11.000
Five foot, ten and a half was the way she looked at that white woman behind the counter. This was like, it was like, it was like, it was like, that's what she could do.

01:37:11.000 --> 01:37:26.000
It was like she looked at this other white person like she was a piece of dirt and how dare she question, how dare she even think about. I mean, that's the other side of Anne.

01:37:26.000 --> 01:37:40.000
She had this, that's a kind of instinct she could get. She could become very, for sure. So, so my, my, my answer to your question is that she loved me.

01:37:40.000 --> 01:38:07.000
And the question that I think that she felt that she didn't have to ask anybody's approval. She felt she had the resources in the stature. She felt she was raised in an environment where she was part of the upper class.

01:38:07.000 --> 01:38:22.000
So she tended to look down on everybody else. Classic example. And I say this, just as an, classic example. Her best friend was a woman by the name of Damon Estate Estate.

01:38:22.000 --> 01:38:43.000
Damon Estate Estate was the daughter of the Dole Pineapple people. They were very, very close friends. Back when I got out of, I was ready to graduate from law school. Damon Estate Estate tried to convince. And we should just move to Hawaii. And I said, you know, I said that. I don't know what I wanted to do. I moved to Hawaii.

01:38:43.000 --> 01:38:55.000
I was, she says, look, don't worry about it. We, my family will just, we'll, we'll, we'll, clients and you will build you a house. So forth. You know, we'll just so forth.

01:38:55.000 --> 01:39:10.000
And I didn't even appreciate who Damon Estate Estate was until I began to, until Anne began to tell me. And then I began to understand that aside from some king's trust,

01:39:10.000 --> 01:39:22.000
aside from the trust in Hawaii that the Damon Estate's are the second largest landowners in Hawaii. And that was Anne's friends.

01:39:22.000 --> 01:39:42.000
But those are the, now the other thing was that Anne had lots of left wing friends too. And I think she was.

01:39:42.000 --> 01:39:58.000
