I know you and we're defending this. And I'd love for you to come down and be our law clerk and help us with the defense. And I said, Judge, I'd love to do it, but I'm here in Altadena, California. I can't do it. No way I can do that.

01:53:29.000 --> 01:53:41.000
No, no, you know, this is a, this is, if you met him, I said, no, he says, well, you know, this is a, this is a very special time, you know, and I might be the, anyway, he made a great, and it was very difficult.

01:53:41.000 --> 01:53:53.000
This is the man that recommended me to Boston University of Alaska. This is the person who was a judge, he was a senior. I mean, he was very, very great partner. For me to say no to him, you know, it was, was not easy.

01:53:53.000 --> 01:54:04.000
But I said, no, I couldn't, I said, no, for practical purpose, I couldn't go. And so my wife at that time was pregnant with our second child. I was comfortable going.

01:54:04.000 --> 01:54:22.000
And you knew obviously my, no, I never met him before. I vaguely heard of him. You know, I tell everybody I was in law school from 1956 and 1959. I didn't know anything. I mean, I knew about the Montgomery bus boycott, but I was studying. I didn't have time to follow the legal feature. What he's doing?

01:54:22.000 --> 01:54:36.000
You know, I mean, I was really not focused on that, you know. So the judge was very disappointed in me. The next thing I know it, that was on a Thursday night on Friday morning. I got another call from the judge and he says, Clarence, I did not know it at the time of our conversation.

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:43.000
But Dr. King is on his way to California right now. He has a speaking engagement at the World Affairs Council.

01:54:43.000 --> 01:55:04.000
And I told on Saturday evening and I told him, if he does nothing else before he goes through the speaking engagement. And I think he's also going to feature out there. He says, he says, I told him he has to find a way in meeting and talking to you. So I'm thinking to myself, okay, you know what I mean? I'm listening to the judge. And I'm thinking to myself after it.

01:55:04.000 --> 01:55:19.000
Why would the judge do that? You know, he's thinking as well. Anyway, maybe just Martin King is going to change my mind. So Friday night doorbell rings. Martin King comes to my home and I'll be in California.

01:55:20.000 --> 01:55:40.000
He comes in and he says, you know, he produces himself and comes in with a fellow by the name of Bernard Lee. He comes in to the six around the coffee table on the by the way at that time in February, 1960. Under all classic criteria.

01:55:41.000 --> 01:56:05.000
He was a celebrity. He went on the cover of Look, Life, and Time magazines. Plus he had been successful in Montgomery Buzz point got with Rosa Parks. Plus in addition to Supreme Court 1957, it ended down a decision outlawing segregation into state bus transit. He was riding high this feature from Montgomery, okay, in 1960.

