Stanley Levison and Bayard Rustin as they hold on Dr. King, you can't go.

02:06:16.000 --> 02:06:18.000
You need to stay here.

02:06:18.000 --> 02:06:26.000
And what we'll do is we'll give you a vacation in the states

02:06:26.000 --> 02:06:31.000
and we'll ask Clarence and his wife to vacate their newly constructed homes.

02:06:31.000 --> 02:06:34.000
So that you and your family can stay there.

02:06:34.000 --> 02:06:38.000
The only problem is nobody asked, nobody talked to me.

02:06:38.000 --> 02:06:43.000
Okay? So the next thing I know is that Stanley Levison says that he and Bayard,

02:06:43.000 --> 02:06:48.000
and others have decided that we had to leave our home so that's Coretta

02:06:48.000 --> 02:06:51.000
and Dr. King and their poor children could stay in our house.

02:06:51.000 --> 02:06:56.000
And the principal political reason was that we would have access to him domestically.

02:06:56.000 --> 02:07:00.000
And he would be able to have a vacation while still being available

02:07:00.000 --> 02:07:02.000
from Washington Washington.

02:07:02.000 --> 02:07:07.000
And so during that period of time, he was writing a book, among other things,

02:07:07.000 --> 02:07:13.000
and during that period of time, Stanley Levison and I, particularly,

02:07:13.000 --> 02:07:18.000
even though again two months earlier on June 22nd,

02:07:18.000 --> 02:07:24.000
Stanley had been the subject of a private conversation between President Kennedy.

02:07:25.000 --> 02:07:28.000
And Dr. King.

02:07:28.000 --> 02:07:32.000
And that conversation very directly was that the president told him

02:07:32.000 --> 02:07:35.000
that he had to get rid of Stanley Levison and Jack O'Dell

02:07:35.000 --> 02:07:38.000
that they had reliable information with the FBI.

02:07:38.000 --> 02:07:41.000
Stanley Levison was a high ranking member of the Communist Party,

02:07:41.000 --> 02:07:43.000
and so was Jack O'Dell.

02:07:43.000 --> 02:07:47.000
And so that was like a time bomb.

02:07:47.000 --> 02:07:53.000
Not a time bomb was like a meager explosion that somewhat derailed

02:07:53.000 --> 02:08:00.000
things at the point, but the point is, as the march approached,

02:08:00.000 --> 02:08:06.000
Stanley and I can, although it was decided that Stanley would step back

02:08:06.000 --> 02:08:08.000
with his consent, with his urging.

02:08:08.000 --> 02:08:13.000
Dr. King did not want to reduce his oral context of Stanley.

02:08:13.000 --> 02:08:15.000
He did not want to sever a direct army.

02:08:15.000 --> 02:08:17.000
He was very much adamant again.

02:08:17.000 --> 02:08:22.000
But Stanley, his attitude was, listen, the movement you're leading is more important.

02:08:22.000 --> 02:08:25.000
And me or the relationship you and I have.

02:08:25.000 --> 02:08:28.000
This is what the president, Attorney General, want, let's give it to him,

02:08:28.000 --> 02:08:29.000
let's move on.

02:08:29.000 --> 02:08:31.000
We have more important things to do.

02:08:31.000 --> 02:08:35.000
But meanwhile, Stanley and I talked virtually every day,

02:08:35.000 --> 02:08:37.000
and Matt is involving Dr. King.

02:08:37.000 --> 02:08:44.000
And at some point in those discussions, what he would say at the march came up.

02:08:44.000 --> 02:08:50.000
And the question was really a policy question.

02:08:51.000 --> 02:08:59.000
What kind of speech, you know, you're going to give a public sermon.

02:08:59.000 --> 02:09:02.000
You're going to give a political treatise of what kind of speech you're going to make.

02:09:02.000 --> 02:09:06.000
What's the one from the beginning that he would be the last speaker of the day?

02:09:06.000 --> 02:09:08.000
Oh no, no, no, no, you asked it.

02:09:08.000 --> 02:09:12.000
You asked the question that maybe you don't know how pregnant it is with controversy.

02:09:12.000 --> 02:09:19.000
Okay, as a matter of fact, there were, there came a time

02:09:19.000 --> 02:09:28.000
when conservative clergymen in the March committee, through the organizations,

02:09:28.000 --> 02:09:34.000
they wanted, they put a proposal out that there should be ex number speakers,

02:09:34.000 --> 02:09:40.000
let's say 12 speakers or 10 speakers, and each should have no more than eight minutes.

02:09:40.000 --> 02:09:44.000
And they had proposed that Dr. King be in the middle.

02:09:44.000 --> 02:09:48.000
And I heard this, I heard that this is going to be a proposal.

02:09:48.000 --> 02:09:52.000
When I heard this, and by Bayard Rustin who shared this with me,

02:09:52.000 --> 02:09:57.000
and I persuaded Dr. King, I don't want you to come to this meeting of the march committee.

02:09:57.000 --> 02:09:59.000
It's better that you not come.

02:09:59.000 --> 02:10:01.000
And I'm listening.

02:10:01.000 --> 02:10:08.000
And they said, well, we think that this is the way it should be and so forth.

02:10:08.000 --> 02:10:15.000
And I clearly got the sense that there was an effort, I'm not sure other than Ego what the reason was,

02:10:15.000 --> 02:10:18.000
that they wanted to marginalize Dr. King.

02:10:18.000 --> 02:10:21.000
They didn't, they wanted to prevent him from being the last speaker.

02:10:21.000 --> 02:10:24.000
And they didn't, and they wanted to marginalize him.

02:10:24.000 --> 02:10:29.000
So Dr. King wasn't there, so I could say things that he certainly wouldn't say at this meeting.

02:10:29.000 --> 02:10:31.000
And who is there? Who is there?

02:10:31.000 --> 02:10:42.000
They is a bad Russian, Walter Reuther, a yes, wired worker, A. Philip Randolph, a Cleveland Robinson,

02:10:43.000 --> 02:10:53.000
a representative from the UAW, representatives from a core, representatives of student on violent coordinate committee, representatives from the NAACP,

02:10:53.000 --> 02:11:01.000
and representatives of several of the local black churches and representatives from the diocese, the Catholic diocese in the year, okay?

02:11:01.000 --> 02:11:05.000
And someone from the American Jewish Congress.

02:11:06.000 --> 02:11:13.000
But the black clergy representatives were the ones who were trying to manipulate the power in my observation.

02:11:13.000 --> 02:11:23.000
They made a proposal that the each person be allowed the same amount of speech and they had proposed that Dr. King be in the middle of that.

02:11:23.000 --> 02:11:29.000
So while this discussion is going on, I just said, excuse me, gentlemen, I said,

02:11:29.000 --> 02:11:33.000
you've all heard Dr. King speak, have you, have you, have all of you in this room heard Dr. King speak?

02:11:33.000 --> 02:11:38.000
Well, tell me something, do you really want to, do you really want to follow Dr. King?

02:11:38.000 --> 02:11:43.000
I said now in my, when I'm not doing civil rights work, I said I have a law practice with two other partners,

02:11:43.000 --> 02:11:49.000
and we do a lot of entertainment, working with representatives of all artists and performing artists.

02:11:49.000 --> 02:11:57.000
And I said in the concert business, in the concert business, there's something called an opening act and a major act.

02:11:57.000 --> 02:12:02.000
And I said, do you really want to follow Dr. King?

02:12:02.000 --> 02:12:10.000
And I said, well, why do you say that? I said, well, because quite frankly, you're in the risk that after he speaks, I just turned it off.

02:12:10.000 --> 02:12:25.000
After he speaks, people will, so with some, with some begrudging consent, and what tip the discussion was a Phil Randolph.

02:12:25.000 --> 02:12:34.000
Because yes, I think that, I think that brother Martin should come, and I agree with, I agree with Clarence Jones, most of these people.

02:12:34.000 --> 02:12:39.000
And I don't want to offend anybody in this room, but most of the people are coming from all over the country.

02:12:39.000 --> 02:12:45.000
They're coming to hear Dr. King, and we should have him as a last speaker.

02:12:45.000 --> 02:12:59.000
And the preparation of the speech was, some people think that Dr. King, the Washington, is set down and just going to write the speech.

02:12:59.000 --> 02:13:14.000
He was at the Willard Hotel, working on his speech, but the speech he was working on, incorporated, or I provided him with information, that he could use, if he chose to.

02:13:14.000 --> 02:13:26.000
In the speech that he was preparing. I did not know, until I was standing 50 feet behind him, and he actually spoke.

02:13:26.000 --> 02:13:38.000
And I listened very carefully. I did not know that after his perfunctory interuptory remarks, that as he began speaking,

02:13:38.000 --> 02:13:48.000
the first opening, six or seven paragraphs or more, with the draft paragraphs, which I put in summary form for him to use.

02:13:48.000 --> 02:13:59.000
Whether he was tired, whether he liked it, or whether he just, he was pressed for time, but he didn't change his sentence.

02:13:59.000 --> 02:14:15.000
Not a word, a paragraph, or a comma. He spoke verbatim. What I had prepared, but what I had prepared was a summary of what we had discussed several times about the kind of things that he should say.

02:14:15.000 --> 02:14:34.000
I just used a certain degree of drama because I had had the problem of raising bail money. I had to go in the bail money, and I remember going to the Chase Manhattan Bank, to raise some bail money coming up to New York and going in and seeing money from Florida's ceiling.

02:14:34.000 --> 02:14:55.000
And so when I was drafted, this I said, I can't believe, drafted the suggested paragraph, the language I said, I can't believe that we have assembled here today to redeem the promissory note, to which the signers of the Declaration of Independence were heirs.

02:14:55.000 --> 02:15:10.000
And what's the present generation, is an air to this promissory note, I cannot believe that in the vaults of justice in the United States that the bank of justice insufficient funds.

02:15:13.000 --> 02:15:24.000
So he's speaking. That's the first time I had an idea that he was going to incorporate the actual suggested language, had no idea until then.

02:15:24.000 --> 02:15:27.000
Because your normal process is you give him a draft and you'd work with this.

02:15:27.000 --> 02:15:41.000
Yeah, yeah, right, right, right, right, right, right, right. And this is the normal process too. He didn't use everything. He didn't use all of the paragraphs, but he used the first six or seven of the paragraphs, and then he added his own paragraphs.

02:15:41.000 --> 02:15:51.000
And then as he is speaking from this written, paired text, his favorite gospel singer, Mahalia Jackson, shout-out to him. She had performed earlier on the program.

02:15:51.000 --> 02:16:12.000
Tell him about the dream, Martin, tell him about the dream. And I'm watching him. And in real time, he acknowledges her. But then he takes the prepared written text and moves it to the left side of the lectern and grabs the left side of the lectern and starts to speak.

02:16:12.000 --> 02:16:19.000
And I turned to the person sitting next to me, who were standing next to me, whoever that person was, that they're still living.

02:16:19.000 --> 02:16:31.000
I said, these people don't know it, but they're about ready to go to church. And I said that because I saw Dr. King's body language change.

02:16:31.000 --> 02:16:47.000
So that the part of the speech, that speech, that the nation in the world celebrates the so-called I have a dream speech, was completely spontaneous, was completely extemporaneous.

02:16:47.000 --> 02:17:14.000
And but for the last part, where he's looking at notes in the end about this Negro, he was quoting a poem about a new free and last free at last, which is a, which is a, from a, from a Protestant clergyman many years earlier, everything else was spontaneous, everything.

02:17:14.000 --> 02:17:25.000
Now, as I say in my book, behind the dream, the baking of the speech, the transformation. You know, I heard Martin King and saw him speak many times.

02:17:25.000 --> 02:17:41.000
I'm not suggesting, well, whatever your belief, whatever your religious belief, if any, whatever your belief in spirituality or transcendentalism, if any, I can only tell you what I experienced and what I saw.

02:17:41.000 --> 02:17:53.000
And what I experienced and what I saw, I had never up until that time in my life, anyone, including Dr. King, I had never heard Dr. King speak that way before.

02:17:53.000 --> 02:18:08.000
It is as if some cosmic, powerful force came down and took over his body, that there was the same body I was looking at, but something had taken it over.

02:18:08.000 --> 02:18:35.000
Because the words, the way he said it, was so powerful. And I think it was the combination of the beauty of the day, two or three o'clock in the afternoon, the beauty of the day, the citus, the venue, the Lincoln Memorial,

02:18:35.000 --> 02:18:45.000
the more than 250,000 people you have to sign at that time, no place in America had that many people ever assembled in one place at one time.

02:18:45.000 --> 02:19:04.000
Peacefully, 25% of whom were white, no place. And something happened in the interaction between what Martin was saying in that audience, so that never, ever again,

02:19:04.000 --> 02:19:31.000
until he is a, never again in his lifetime, had I ever heard him speak that way. Now people will say, well, you know, he gave a very moving speech in April 3rd, 1968 in Mason Temple, moving speech, depressed, talk about I've been to the mountain top, in terms of the political content, well, a lot of from the Birmingham Jail was much more profound political statement.

02:19:31.000 --> 02:19:44.000
Beyond Vietnam" speech, A Time to Break Silence much more political profound statement on non-violence both internationally and nationally.

02:19:45.000 --> 02:20:04.000
But the power of his simple message, because he was calling for America, he was summoning America's conscience, so that the nation could be as good as it was intended to be.

02:20:05.000 --> 02:20:32.000
I don't know whether I've said this to you before, but the genius of Martin Luther King, Jr., the political genius was that he knew, and we knew, that no matter how compelling and how fair the case for any racial segregation was on his merits, there was no way the 12% of the population was going to impose that point of view, nobody how fair and compelling on the merits.

02:20:33.000 --> 02:20:46.000
On 88% of the population was going to happen, in spite of our friends on the black left and the white left who said, the only way to only think the white man understands is a gun and a kick in a butt.

02:20:46.000 --> 02:20:53.000
Anyone who wanted to cancel violence on the part of 12% of the population against 88% of the population is counseling political suicide.

02:20:54.000 --> 02:21:13.000
Yes, we were students of the end of the revolution of the end of the developed country, we were students of the Algeria, Zimbabwe, Kenya, Ghana, Egypt, we understood.

02:21:14.000 --> 02:21:18.000
But we understood the peculiarities of the American experience.

02:21:20.000 --> 02:21:42.000
So therefore, the genius of Martin Luther King was that he would summon the conscience of America through peaceful, non-violent confrontation with racial segregation, so that the conscience of the 88% of the country,

02:21:43.000 --> 02:22:02.000
would be forced to see the contradiction between the way in which it treated 12% of its people, people of color, and the command the mints in the Declaration of Independence and our Constitution.

02:22:03.000 --> 02:22:12.000
But guess what? To Dr. King, it wasn't a constitutional or legal question for America. It was a moral question.

02:22:13.000 --> 02:22:28.000
And he raised the level, he raised in the level of the 88% raised the question in their minds, is whether this is the kind of nation they want to be.

02:22:29.000 --> 02:22:44.000
Is it morally right to deny 12% of the population full access to equal protection of the laws, equal opportunity for both solely based on the color of the skin?

02:22:47.000 --> 02:22:49.000
That was his political genius.

02:22:50.000 --> 02:22:59.000
I guess I told you the phrase from the boys about the lions don't tell this story, I've told you that.

02:23:03.000 --> 02:23:18.000
I think it's important for future generations that they be unambiguously clear as to the power and the meaning of the nation.

02:23:20.000 --> 02:23:23.000
Of the I have a gene speech in the March on Washington.

02:23:24.000 --> 02:23:32.000
I don't want people to get caught up in the so-called nostalgia of commemorating the 50th anniversary of the March,

02:23:35.000 --> 02:23:41.000
and overlook the centrality of what that was about.

02:23:42.000 --> 02:23:51.000
Was it the greatest speech in terms of political content? I don't think so.

02:23:54.000 --> 02:24:04.000
But what Martin King did, is that I talk about him having taken America on a journey to overcome.

02:24:05.000 --> 02:24:10.000
He had to appreciate the commemoration of Martin King's 50th anniversary.

02:24:10.000 --> 02:24:13.000
He had to understand what happened, what America was going through.

02:24:13.000 --> 02:24:18.000
It was America going through America had become like a dysfunctional alcoholic or drug addict.

02:24:18.000 --> 02:24:23.000
It had become addicted on racial segregation dependency.

02:24:25.000 --> 02:24:31.000
And it tried unsuccessfully to break its addiction and dependency.

02:24:35.000 --> 02:24:50.000
And Martin King took America conscience by the hand and said, I'm going to take you on a road of peaceful, redemptive recovery to recover your soul.

02:24:52.000 --> 02:25:01.000
And I'm going to do this non-violently. I'm going to do it, telling you I love you every step of the way.

02:25:02.000 --> 02:25:09.000
I'm going to do it to let you know no matter what you say to me, no matter what you do to me.

02:25:10.000 --> 02:25:18.000
You can call me all sorts of names. You can put me in jail. You can bomb my house. You can threaten me.

02:25:19.000 --> 02:25:22.000
But at the end of all those things, I'm still going to love you.

02:25:24.000 --> 02:25:29.000
Because my compassion and love for your soul and for you to redeem,

02:25:32.000 --> 02:25:44.000
the best of what this country, to be my compassion, my commitment to do that, is greater than you're greater and stronger than anything you can do to me.

02:25:45.000 --> 02:25:49.000
Greater than stronger. Because I believe in you, America.

02:25:50.000 --> 02:25:58.000
You may not believe in yourself, but I can believe in you. And so that when I tell you I have a dream, I'm not speaking about the present tense.

02:25:59.000 --> 02:26:05.000
I'm speaking prophetically in the future. I know I have absolute confidence.

02:26:06.000 --> 02:26:16.000
Not now, maybe on August 28th, 1963. But I believe that one day, my four children, I may be alive, I may not be alive.

02:26:17.000 --> 02:26:27.000
We may not be around, you don't know, but one day, this country that I believe in, my four children will be judged by the content of their character and not by the color of their skin.

02:26:28.000 --> 02:26:34.000
It may not be happening today, it may not happen tomorrow, it may not happen in your lifetime or my lifetime.

02:26:37.000 --> 02:26:50.000
But one day, your conscience will come to see the immorality of racial segregation, the immorality of racism.

02:26:51.000 --> 02:27:02.000
So that one day, the great great grand sons of slaves and the great great grand sons of slave owners will sit, will sit down one day at the table of brotherhood.

02:27:04.000 --> 02:27:12.000
I believe that that will happen, America. Even though you may at this time, may not believe in yourself.

02:27:13.000 --> 02:27:21.000
That's, you want to commemorate the 50th anniversary of Martin King, that's what you got to remember.

02:27:23.000 --> 02:27:33.000
You got to remember, in 1963, Martin King in Birmingham put a moral stake in the ground.

02:27:34.000 --> 02:27:40.000
They know on the top that stake was a moral compass.

02:27:42.000 --> 02:27:46.000
Okay? And that a moral compass became a moral compass.

02:27:48.000 --> 02:28:02.000
And what he did was to show the way of how we have got to live up to be the best that we can be in.

02:28:04.000 --> 02:28:10.000
Otherwise, the country is not going to be governable.

02:28:12.000 --> 02:28:19.000
It's not a question of white people having power over white people.

02:28:20.000 --> 02:28:24.000
It's not a question of white people having power over black people.

02:28:24.000 --> 02:28:41.000
It's a question of co-equally participating in a power based on the indestructible commitment to the uniqueness of the speciality and dignity of the human personality.

02:28:41.000 --> 02:28:47.000
Everybody, everybody is somebody.

02:28:48.000 --> 02:29:00.000
So that in 2013, when I hear, particularly people from the African-American conservative church community,

02:29:02.000 --> 02:29:11.000
tell me that it's against God's will, that homosexuality is a sin. It's against God's will.

02:29:12.000 --> 02:29:27.000
And I am never going to be in support of same-sex marriage. I'm never going to be in support. Homosexuality is a sin.

02:29:28.000 --> 02:29:45.000
So I say to them, I was raised in a Christian religious principle. And I was raised to believe that we were all created in God's image.

02:29:46.000 --> 02:30:03.000
So tell me those of you who are so opposed to the LGBT people, isn't it funny that God must really love gay and lesbian people?

02:30:04.000 --> 02:30:10.000
Because otherwise, why would he keep creating so many of them? I arrest my case.

02:30:19.000 --> 02:30:31.000
The commemoration of this anniversary is a commemoration to America's quintessential pre-immun and a puzzle of nonviolence.

02:30:34.000 --> 02:30:57.000
And just as the nation had to deal with asking itself, what kind of people are we when it looked at, on the front pages of his newspapers, of firehows or slamming little black boys and girls against the walls, Birmingham, Alabama, or police dogs against black boys and girls who are demonstrating peacefully?

02:30:58.000 --> 02:31:06.000
Just as the nation had to ask itself, what kind of nation are we that we would do this?

02:31:11.000 --> 02:31:26.000
After Newtown, Connecticut, when you have 20 babies and 16 adult schools, you want to commemorate the Fiftieth Anniversary of Martin King's legacy, knowing that he was the pre-eminent apostle of nonviolence.

02:31:28.000 --> 02:31:36.000
You have to ask yourself, what kind of nation are we that we would prevent this to happen?

02:31:38.000 --> 02:31:56.000
So I don't know what different people are going to be doing on the 28th of August, 2013 in Birmingham and Cleveland, Ohio and Washington D.C., and Philadelphia and all the nations throughout all the countries and communities across this nation.

02:31:57.000 --> 02:32:16.000
But I can tell you one thing, there can be no more true commemoration, to a legacy than if this nation like the executive in the movie Network.

02:32:17.000 --> 02:32:26.000
If a vote will be majority of American people on the 28th of August, 2013 saying enough is enough.

02:32:27.000 --> 02:32:39.000
I'm mad as hell and I'm not going to take it anymore". Violence is destroying this great country.

02:32:39.000 --> 02:33:04.000
It would be a sacrilege to go through the motions of commemorating his legacy without tying the legacy to the existential violence that is in our country today, the ubiquitous presence of violence.

02:33:05.000 --> 02:33:11.000
And we can do something about it. We can do something about it.

02:33:12.000 --> 02:33:20.000
Martin King would say, come on America, you're better than this. We don't have to continue gun violence.

02:33:21.000 --> 02:33:27.000
We don't have to continue racial segregation. We can end it if we want to.

02:33:28.000 --> 02:33:34.000
So I don't want to hear, we should overcome and I don't want to hear all these commemorative songs.

02:33:35.000 --> 02:33:53.000
What is going to be done? 24-7, August 28, 2013 to deal with the question of the ubiquitous violence that is affecting our young people particularly.

02:33:54.000 --> 02:34:06.000
And the unevenness of the effects of that violence. In some cases, read readily, it has to be clinically described as black on black violence.

02:34:08.000 --> 02:34:21.000
What do I mean? I mean by young black people, men, using guns to kill one another over some failed drug deal or over somebody stepped on their sneakers

02:34:21.000 --> 02:34:26.000
or some crazy nonsense.

02:34:29.000 --> 02:34:36.000
You want to honor the memory of Dr. King's I have a dream speech.

02:34:37.000 --> 02:34:50.000
Then you have the courage to recognize the fundamental qualitative changes that have taken place in many of the households in the African-American community.

02:34:52.000 --> 02:35:03.000
And that is the substantial destruction of the family structure with a male house, a male in the house on a constant basis.

02:35:04.000 --> 02:35:10.000
I'm not talking about husband and wife, I'm talking about a responsible male, responsible female.

02:35:13.000 --> 02:35:20.000
So that for example, here in San Francisco, you have an organization called the Omega Boys Club.

02:35:21.000 --> 02:35:50.000
And by Dr. Joseph Marshall Jr, he recognizes this. He recognizes that if you ever want to have a chance of saving the generation of Caribbean over youth, you've got to find a substitute equivalent to the parental structure of discipline which they don't have.

02:35:51.000 --> 02:36:03.000
So that in effect, the programs he offers at the Boys Club is the program of parental or adult structure discipline that they don't get at home.

02:36:04.000 --> 02:36:11.000
But that adult structure, difficult, is enough to keep them alive and free.

02:36:11.000 --> 02:36:28.000
So I was once having a discussion with Dr. Marshall, which I said, you know, Joe, the most important days in the most important historical days in the history of the African-American nation, African-American people, 1619 in the United States, in 1863, the Emancipation Proclamation, he said, no, no, no, clients.

02:36:28.000 --> 02:36:41.000
You omitted a very important day, and he says, what said he says, 1980, I said, what happened in 1980? Is that some crack cocaine is introduced into the African-American community? That's so fundamentally changed.

02:36:41.000 --> 02:37:05.000
To be a good teacher, Dr. King once said to me, you not only need to know your scripture, and you need to be conversant with the underlying teachings, but you have to have the ability to tell your audience a story.

02:37:05.000 --> 02:37:20.000
You got to tell the story, and the story can be any number of things. The story can be about redemption, redemption, the story can be about, but you got it. You got to tell a story to people can buy into.

02:37:20.000 --> 02:37:48.000
So I am suggesting for those people who listen and read about this time in American history, as we approach the 50th anniversary of the I have a dream speech, that the story of this generation is the story of this extraordinary man who sought to save the soul of America. That's the story.

02:37:50.000 --> 02:37:57.000
Unfortunately, I am about 5-1 minute.

02:37:57.000 --> 02:38:06.000
We allow us to sign, I am going to sign, so you can go.

02:38:06.000 --> 02:38:22.000
What are the parts of Dr. King's journey, as you are talking about his journey and his legacy? Do we need to honor, as we think about him at this time, for the African-American anniversary?

02:38:22.000 --> 02:38:26.000
Are there other works such as his anti-Hiswar?

02:38:26.000 --> 02:38:40.000
No, no, no, no, no, what you have to honor is his unshakable commitment to end the inequity of wealth disparity.

02:38:40.000 --> 02:39:01.000
At the time of his assassination, he was working the template that he was involved in, of course, was Memphis sanitation workers' strike, but that was just an template of an example to highlight the issue of wealth and income disparity in this nation.

02:39:01.000 --> 02:39:15.000
Ironically, the movement of Occupy Wall Street, that's what it was about.

02:39:15.000 --> 02:39:29.000
That's what it was about, and by the way, this was not a movement of impoverished black people.

02:39:29.000 --> 02:39:50.000
This is not a movement of impoverished white people. This is a movement of largely middle class, principally white people, who somehow began to see that there's something very unfair about a system of which they play by all of the rules.

02:39:50.000 --> 02:40:09.000
They go and get a good education. They keep themselves out of trouble, and they try to apply their skills, and they recognize that even if they do everything that they've asked to be done, they're going to have at best a marginal participation in the benefits of this country.

02:40:09.000 --> 02:40:15.000
And that's not morally right.

02:40:15.000 --> 02:40:20.000
Listen to me. That's not morally right.

02:40:20.000 --> 02:40:28.000
So what other things should we think about as legacy? He's unshakable. Come here.

02:40:28.000 --> 02:40:41.000
What prompted his opposition, public opposition to the war in Vietnam, was not only his opposition and the test of the application of violence on an international scale, but he was not stupid.

02:40:41.000 --> 02:40:58.000
He recognized that no matter what Lyndon Johnson said in his heart about the war in poverty, there was no way that a war in poverty can be fought when you're taking the resources, the dollars of the treasury of the United States, and you're taking those dollars to buy armaments.

02:40:58.000 --> 02:41:02.000
But there's no way. There's no way. So it's a sham.

02:41:02.000 --> 02:41:19.000
So again, if you the reason he opposed the war was a moral reason. He realized aside from his absolute opposition, the violence he realized that it was, it was just impossible.

02:41:19.000 --> 02:41:35.000
It was politically and economically impossible for the president of the United States to utter well-meaning words about fighting property when there was no money to do it. It was being spent to kill North Vietnamese.

02:41:35.000 --> 02:41:52.000
So that's the other part of his legacy. And of course, militarism.

02:41:52.000 --> 02:42:09.000
